Description.Column2: On-demand by user with latest available data.
List of volcanoes that have erupted in the past 10,000 years.
Special data product designed for use by Volcanic Ash Advisory Centers (ICAO IAVW).
The database is maintained by the Global Volcanism Program and does not represent any formal position by the International Civil Aviation Organization.
Unique 6-digit identification number maintained by GVP, based on a numbering system implemented in 2013.
Old-style volcano number. Provided for compatibility purposes.  "NULL" indicates a new volcano has been added to the database recently, therefore it does not have an old number.
Preferred volcano name, as determined by the Global Volcanism Program (all uppercase letters with no special characters or apostrophes).
Name of country. Multiple states (separated by a dash) indicate a volcano located along the border.

Geographical area description based on the global distribution of Holocene volcanoes; regions and subregions were originally organized and defined by IAVCEI in the Catalog of Active Volcanoes of the World. This geographic descriptor carries no political meaning, and is only intended to identify the broad volcanic area using common geographic names.
Usually the highest point of the volcano, given in meters relative to mean sea level. Negative numbers indicate a submarine volcano.

Latitude and longitude given in degrees (all positive values), minutes, and seconds, with the N/S or E/W specifically designated. Decimal degree fields are also provided for maximum flexibility, with negative values as appropriate.
The numbering style has been changed with the November 2013 data release, to ensure unique and unchanging numbers in the future.

The coordinates given may not correspond to the summit for volcanoes that do not exhibit a classic cone morphology. For example, the location of a volcanic field is given as its center point, although the high point could be a cone at some distance away.
Many eruptions do not originate from the summit (coordinates given), but rather from flank locations.
Volcano numbers are linked to the GVP website volcano profile pages, which provide geological background, recent reports, more detailed coordinates, and eruptive history for each volcano.
